  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>

        <div xml:id="AN192.2-kilavi">
          <p type="edition">tōḻi talaimakaḷaic ceṟippu aṟivuṟīi iravukkuṟi maṟuttatu.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">How the confidante refused a night tryst by informing HIM of [her] confinement.</p>
        </div>
        <div xml:id="AN192.2">
      <lg type="edition">
        <l>matiyarum paṉṉa mācaṟu cuṭarnutal</l>
        <l>poṉṉēr vaṇṇaṅ koṇṭaṉ ṟaṉṉō</l>
        <l>yāṅkā kuvaḷko ṟāṉē vicumpi</l>
        <l>ṉeyyā varivi laṉṉa paintārc</l>
        <l>cevvāyc ciṟukiḷi citaiya vāṅkip</l>
        <l>poṟaimelin tiṭṭa puṉpuṟap peruṅkural</l>
        <l>vaḷaiciṟai vāraṇaṅ kiḷaiyoṭu kavara</l>
        <l>vēṉalu miṟaṅkupoṟai yiṟuttaṉa pāṉā</l>
        <l>ṇīvan taḷikkuvai yeṉiṉē mālvarai</l>
        <l>maipaṭu viṭarakan tuḻaii yoyyeṉa</l>
        <l>varuvi tanta varavumiḻ tirumaṇi</l>
        <l>peruvaraic ciṟukuṭi ma<supplied>ru</supplied>ṅkuviḷak kuṟuttali</l>
        <l>ṉiravu muṭintaṉa ḷaḷiya ḷuravuppeya</l>
        <l>lurumiṟai koṇṭa vuyarcimaip</l>
        <l>perumalai nāṭaniṉ malarnta mārpē.</l>
      </lg>
      <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
        <l>Like the bud of the moon, [her] flawless glowing forehead, (1)</l>
        <l>it has taken on a gold-like colour, alas. (2)</l>
        <l>What shall become of her? (3a-c)</l>
        <l>Bending over, to be spoilt by little parakeets with red beaks (5)</l>
        <l>[and] green garlands, like the striped bow in the sky that is not discharged, (3df.)</l>
        <l>as the curvy-winged fowl with [their] relatives seize (7)</l>
        <l>the low-backed big ears that are weakened by [their] burden, (6)</l>
        <l>all the millet [stalks] have begun to break under [their] inclining burden. (8a-c)</l>
        <l>If you say you will take care to come at midnight, (8d-9c)</l>
        <l>because the light of the brilliant gem spit by the snake, that was brought by the waterfall</l>
        <l>noisily stirring within the shrouded clefts of the great mountain,</l>
        <l>falls on the side of the little hamlet in the big mountains, (9d-12)</l>
        <l>she would be destroyed at night too, pitiable she, (13a-c)</l>
        <l>– by your blossoming chest, o man from a land of big mountains, (15)</l>
        <l>with high peaks that strong rain [and] thunder take as [their] seat. (13df.)</l>
      </lg>
        </div>
